	abstract = {The 2019 novel coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2, which causes the disease COVID-19) has been spreading at an exponential rate around the world since its outbreak in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.1 As of April 4, 2020, more than 1 000 000 cases of COVID-19 have been confirmed in more than 150 countries, resulting in more than 50 000 deaths. On March 11, 2020, the World Health Organization declared COVID-19 a pandemic, and US president Donald Trump declared a national emergency on March 13.There is no question that it is important for China and other countries to work together to stop the spread of COVID-19, and there is much to commend about the international response to the virus. That effort has to, definitionally, involve a focus on disease containment in China and in travel to and from China. However, one ofthe unintended emerging consequences of the global response to this pandemic has been increasing reports around the world of racism and xenophobia against Asian people, particularly people of Chinese descent. On social media platforms such as Twitter and Facebook, anti-Chinese sentiment has been growing since the virus outbreak, perpetuating the stereotype that Chinese people are unclean and disease ridden. Some news articles in the United States, Australia, and France have used racist terms such as "China virus" and "yellow alert." There were multiple incidents of hatred and violence against people of Asian descent because of COVID-19 around the world (see the Appendix, available as a supplement to the online version of this article at http://www.ajph. org). As SARS-CoV-2 infects more and more people worldwide, episodes of racism against people of Asian descent may continue to grow, potentially exacerbated by fear and disinformation about the virus.Racism is an important determinant of health. Growing research shows that racism and racial discrimination have adverse effects on both the mental and physical health of those targeted by it. However, most studies on racism in the United States have focused on African Americans, and few studies have assessed the impact of racism on population health among other racial/ethnic groups such as Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders. There is no reason to suspect that racism does not have similar adverse health effects across different population groups; thus, racism directed at people of Asian descent during this outbreak should be a cause for alarm.},
